{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"95cc73e1-086a-44b3-a222-acbc93afd274","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the system automatically generates a **crash report**. Look here:\n\n1. **User-level reports:**\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **System-level reports:**\n   ```\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS versions).\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n**For a core dump** (if you need one for `lldb`):\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited        # enable core dumps before running\n/usr/libexec/report_crash   # macOS may still redirect to .ips files\n```\n\n> **Note:** macOS defaults to writing `.ips` crash reports instead of traditional core dumps. The `.ips` files contain the stack trace, register state, and loaded images — often sufficient for diagnosis. If you specifically need a core dump for `lldb`, attach the debugger *before* reproducing the crash: `lldb -- ./YourApp`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9d077444-220a-4194-a56e-3b3c26ad7190","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":340},"id":"276b501d-faa6-4554-9a6f-fd3db97234bf","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:00:48.361Z","parentId":"d7e2a6fd-f48f-4d7e-86d1-ed380c21efd7"}
